<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>135</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-000C</addr>  <route>axt-000C.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>8</month> <day>22</day></date>  <title>Saturated subset (formal topology)</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Given a formal topology <tex>\mathcal{A}  = (S,  \sqsubseteq ,  \lhd )</tex>, a subset <tex>A
   \subseteq  S</tex> is called saturated if it is a fixed point of the <link href="axt-000D.xml" type="local" title="Closure
  operator">closure
  operator</link> associated with <tex>\mathcal{A}</tex>, which is to say it satisfies
  <tex display="block">\mathsf{Clos} _{ \mathcal{A} }(A) = A.</tex></p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>136</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-000D</addr>  <route>axt-000D.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>8</month> <day>22</day></date>  <title>Closure operator (formal topology)</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  With any formal topology <tex>\mathcal{A}  = (S,  \sqsubseteq ,  \lhd )</tex>, there is an
  associated closure operator:
  <tex display="block">\mathsf{Clos} _{ \mathcal{A} }(U)  \vcentcolon \equiv   \{  a  \in  S  \mid  a  \lhd  U  \} .</tex></p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>